## Step 2 — ITERATE simulation: Coverage breach

Hypothetical scenario: implementer seeded the org but missed 2 of 8 partner
agency records. Aggregate score is 81% but Coverage hits 16/25, below the
18-point hard-fail floor.

Input JSON to `cli score`:

```json
{
  "scores": [
    {"name": "Coverage", "score": 16, "evidence": "2 of 8 partner agency records missing from org after seed"},
    {"name": "Layout_Completeness", "score": 22, "evidence": "all writeable fields populated except 1 (empty-by-design)"},
    {"name": "Relationship_Integrity", "score": 22, "evidence": "all junction records resolved"},
    {"name": "Realism", "score": 21, "evidence": "Oregon partner names verified"}
  ],
  "dimensions": [
    {"name": "Coverage", "max_points": 25, "hard_fail_floor": 18},
    {"name": "Layout_Completeness", "max_points": 25, "hard_fail_floor": 15},
    {"name": "Relationship_Integrity", "max_points": 25, "hard_fail_floor": 18},
    {"name": "Realism", "max_points": 25, "hard_fail_floor": 12}
  ],
  "tests": {"unit_pass": true, "integration_pass": false, "smoke_pass": true}
}
```

Output:

```json
{
  "verdict": "ITERATE",
  "quality_total": 81,
  "quality_max": 100,
  "quality_pct": 81.0,
  "hard_fail_breaches": [
    "Coverage scored 16 (floor 18)"
  ],
  "spec_defect_reason": null
}
```

CLI exit code: 1 (signals ITERATE to shell pipelines)

**Why this is the right outcome:** Without the floor, 81% would ship.
But 2 missing records = 2 click-path steps that fail on demo day.
The hard-fail floor catches the demo-killer hidden behind a passing
aggregate score.

